 The hit/effect of food scares on price (change to make better/related to changing something) 
 in the UK beef market 
 TimLloydaÂ·*, S. McCorristonb, C.W. Morgana, A.J. Raynera 
 a 
 
 School of Money flow, University of Nottingham, Nottingham NG7 2RD, UK 
 b School of Management and Business, University of Exeter. Exeter, UK 
 
 Abstract 
 This paper thinks about/believes the hit/effect of 'food scares', mostly concerns relating to BSE, on UK beef prices at retail, 
 wholesale and producer levels over the 1990s. Admitting/recognizing/responding to the co-movement that exists between prices in the meat 
 marketing chain, we use a co-integrating (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built), the results of which show the importance of (being talked about a lot on TV, online, etc.) (related to/looking at/thinking about) the 
 safety of food in the transmission of beef prices in the UK. The 'food (being talked about a lot on TV, online, etc.)' index that we use has a marked negative 
 hit/effect on the prices at all levels, a result that is agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with the effect of an inward move/change in the demand function. More than that, 
 the extent of price decline differs/changes between the marketing stages involving that the price spreads rise in response to an increase 
 in the (negative) (being talked about a lot on TV, online, etc.) about food safety. While not a formal test of market power, these (instances of watching, noticing, or making statements) are agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with 
 recent possible results (showing or proving) that market power worsens price changes in the upstream parts/areas for a given change 
 in the retail demand function. The hint/result/effect of these different price changes is that the food safety concerns also cause the 
 marketing margins between the stages to widen. The UK's Competition Commission has (not very long ago) (examined closely) the (very mean, unfair treatment) of 
 market power in the food part/area, motivated mostly by this clearly stated/particular issue.Â© 2001 Elsevier Science B.V. All rights reserved. 
 JEL classification: C32; 110; Qll 
 Keywords: Food scares; Food (being talked about a lot on TV, online, etc.) index; Beef prices; BSE; Price (change to make better/related to changing something) 
 
 1. Introduction 
 
 Over the last few years, issues relating to food safety have 
 risen to the top of the political purpose in many countries, especially in Europe and North America. Much 
 of this (list of things to deal with/desire to reach a goal) has related to the increased knowledge 
 over health, changing dietary patterns and the differences in standards between the countries that lie at the 
 heart of trade arguments. However, maybe the most famous feature of the increased public reaction to food 
 safety is the issue of 'food scares'. This is especially 
 *Corresponding author. Tel.: +44-115-951-5474; 
 fax: +44-115-951-4159. 
 E-mail address: tim.lloyd@nottingham.ac.uk (T. Lloyd). 
 
 the case in Europe, and is showed by the outbreak 
 of BSE in the UK, which according to guesses (DTZ 
 Pieda Consulting, 1998) saw beef consumption fall 
 (for a short time) by 40%, not only in the UK itself, but also 
 in countries such as Germany and Italy which had no 
 reported cases of BSE (at the time). 
 A little bit, the school-related books has responded by paying greater attention to food safety 
 concerns. This has mostly focused on two themes. 
 The first has been to re-visit food demand studies taking into account health-driven changes in dietary patterns. Examples include Brown and Schrader (1990), 
 Burton and Young (1996), Kinnucan et al. (1997) and 
 Rickertsen and von Cramon-Taubadel (2000) among 
 others. The other main theme in the food safety 
 
