 books has been to focus on the appropriate legal/law-based structure for dealing with food safety concerns 
 (see, for example, the symposia published in the American Journal of Farming-based Money flow, December 
 1997). However, to the best of our knowledge, the books has not talked to/looked at the hit/effect of food scares on 
 the prices at different stages of the marketing chain. 
 This is the focus of the present paper which studies 
 the nature of price (change to make better/related to changing something) in the UK beef market 
 in response to the outbreak, increased knowledge and 
 likely effects of BSE. An important feature of the paper is that we think about/believe price (change to make better/related to changing something) at three stages 
 (retail, wholesale and producer) of the beef marketing chain. By doing so, we highlight not only the 
 hit/effect of price (change to make better/related to changing something) but also the effect of food 
 scares on price spreads. Our data show that prices 
 have fallen at all levels in the 1990s but that spreads 
 have not remained constant. Specifically, whereas 
 retail prices have fallen by 18%, wholesale and producer prices have fallen by around 40% each. During 
 this period all spreads have been watched/followed to grow, 
 but the retail-wholesale spread has grown five times 
 more than the wholesale-producer spread. While this 
 price decline is unsurprising in the face of increased 
 personal knowledge, the change in spreads is maybe 
 less obvious. However, as McCorriston et al. (1998) 
 show, this result is agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with the result of 
 the model of up-and-down markets in which a shock to 
 retail demand passes through a chain showed 
 by a price transmission ability to stretch that is greater than 
 togetherness. The value of the ability to stretch depends on many 
 factors, one of which is the degree of market power. 
 In this paper, we present casual (instances of watching, noticing, or making statements) of 
 the data before exploring econometrically the relationships between prices along the UK's meat chain, 
 which are shown to be dependent on the (being talked about a lot on TV, online, etc.) 
 given to issues of food safety. To incorporate this scientifically, we employ a newly developed measure, the 
 'food (being talked about a lot on TV, online, etc.)' index. 
 The nature and timing of this research is smart. There 
 has been debate in the UK relating to the (casual) 
 (instance of watching, noticing, or making a statement) that price changes at the retail stage were 
 smaller than those happening at the farm level. This 
 was a principal reason for the recent Competition 
 Commission question (or investigation), which among the other things 
 (examined closely) the market power in the UK food part/area 
 with a particular focus on the up-and-down relationships. While we present no formal model of the market 
 
 structure in this paper, McCorriston et al. (1998, 1999) 
 have shown that when the markets are (in a way that is not totally pure or totally correct) 
 competitive, price (change to make better/related to changing something) will change/differ  between the 
 parts/areas. 
 Both demand and supply effects are likely to have 
 influenced the pattern of price changes in the beef part/area over the 1990s. Most obviously, the BSE problem is 
 likely to have caused moves/changes in the retail demand function for beef, which will have affected the 
 upstream prices. However, the cost side effects may 
 also be important given new meat part/area rules. 
 These have been introduced to calm people of 
 the safety of British beef in the bad after-effects of the problem and are likely to have increased costs. For example, higher charges for the Meat Cleanliness Service and 
 Specified Risk Material (SRM) disposal, reduced payments for creating and increased transactions costs 
 are commonly-thought to have (risen up/become visible) from the BSE problem 
 (Meat and Animals Commission, 1999). Costs have 
 also increased due to the greater use of Controlled Atmosphere Packaging (CAP). However, in the (not being there; not being present) 
 of reliable guesses the hit/effect of these changes is hard to (check for truth/prove true), not least because partial payment 
 was received by many of those affected. 1 Clearly, in 
 (thinking about/when one thinks about) the hit/effect of food scares on the UK beef 
 part/area, there are likely to be both demand and supply 
 factors deciding/figuring out prices at each up-and-down stage. However, as discussed in the following section, it should 
 not necessarily be expected that these (coming from the outside of something) factors should have a matching hit/effect on prices (and 
 hence price spreads) throughout the marketing chain. 
 More specifically, while the rising costs due to tighter 
 legal/law-based standards will lead to a decrease in price 
 spreads, the move/change of the retail demand function will 
 lead to an increase in price spreads. More than that, even if 
 the shift factors are equi-(fair in amount, related to something else/properly sized compared to something else), these effects 
 will not cancel out, with the retail demand shifts ruling over the hit/effect of the legal/law-based standards. 
 The paper is organised as follows. In Section 2, 
 we briefly survey both the possible and scientific 
 books relating to price (change to make better/related to changing something) in the (up and down) 
 related markets. This hints that even though the 
 prices change in the same direction, the extent of the 
 price changes change/differ  according to the retail stage and 
 hence marketing margins will change. In the case 
