 studied here, marketing margins are expected to increase even if the marketing costs and the retail 
 demand curve move/change to the same extent. This not prevented by/not part of the issue, the nature of the data relating to food scares 
 would suggest that demand shifts are likely to rule. Section 3 presents the data and in Section 4 
 we discuss the (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built) for the scientific analysis. 
 Admitting/recognizing/responding to the co-movement of beef prices at all 
 stages of the chain, we put into use a co-integration (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built) for the scientific analysis, the results of which 
 are reported in Section 5. These show that beef prices 
 do not co-integrate without including a measure 
 of food safety (being talked about a lot on TV, online, etc.) - the food (being talked about a lot on TV, online, etc.) index. 
 The bad effect of the index differs according to 
 the marketing level and may account for the growing 
 price spreads watched/followed scientifically. Section 6 ends/decides by highlighting issues relating to the on-going 
 research. 
 
 2. Price (change to make better/related to changing something): possible 
 and scientific issues 
 2.1. Possible issues 
 In the farming-based money flow/money-based studies books, the most 
 popular (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built) for (thinking about/when one thinks about) the hit/effect of (coming from the outside of something) shocks to the food part/area is in the big picture 
 of the balance displacement models starting 
 with Gardner (1975). The basis of this (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built) 
 is to think about  the hit/effect of price (change to make better/related to changing something) (and 
 corresponding welfare effects) at different stages of 
 the marketing chain and how the farm-retail spread 
 may change as a result. An important feature 
 of the Gardner (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built) relates to the source of 
 the (coming from the outside of something) shocks. Especially, a demand-side 
 shock directly affecting, say, the retail part/area, may 
 have a different effect on retail and farm prices than 
 a supply-side shock starting at the farm part/area. 
 However, one important criticism of the standard 
 balance displacement (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built) is that it assumes 
 that the downstream food market is perfectly competitive. There is increasing (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) that this is not an 
 appropriate description of the food part/area in many 
 developed countries. For example, Bhuyan and Lopez 
 (1997) measure market power across 40 sub-parts/areas 
 of the US food industry and find that in all but three 
 cases, the null guess of competitive behaviour 
 
 349 
 
 can be rejected. Although studies of the food part/area in 
 other developed countries are usually missing, high 
 levels of concentration at least suggest that almost the same 
 things describe the food part/area in most (related to Europe) countries. More than that, the recent (act of asking questions and trying to find the truth about something) by 
 the UK Competition Commission clearly reinforces 
 the bad feeling that market power is a feature of the food 
 part/area in the UK. 
 What difference does this make to our understanding of price (change to make better/related to changing something)? Some studies from 
 the industrial organisation books have shown that 
 (not totally pure/not totally correct) competition has a big impact on 
 price (change to make better/related to changing something). Specifically, under 'reasonable' conditions, for a supply shock, price transmission is reduced if the downstream part/area is seen as 
 market power. (not very long ago), McCorriston et al. (1998) introduce market power into the Gardner (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built); 
 they show that for an increase in costs at the farm 
 level, market power in the downstream food part/area will 
 reduce the level of price (change to make better/related to changing something) compared with 
 the competitive test result. The hint/result/effect is that in 
 the presence of a supply shock at the farm level, the 
 model (describes the future) a narrowing of price spreads. The same 
 holds true for a move/change in the marketing services supply 
 function which takes by force/takes control of the increase in costs due to 
 tighter legal/law-based standards. Under (not totally pure/not totally correct) competition, an increase in the input costs causes retail prices 
 to rise but this increase is (along with something else/related to something else) less than the 
 increase in input costs. As a result, price spreads 
 should narrow where processing costs increase. 
 However, this still leaves open the issue of the 
 source of the (coming from the outside of something) shock. As highlighted above, 
 telling the difference between a demand and cost shock matters. McCorriston et al. (1999) also think about/believe this issue 
 and label price (change to make better/related to changing something) due to a demand shock affecting the retail part/area as a 'pass-back' effect. They 
 show formally that for an inward move/change in the demand 
 function, market power in the downstream food part/area 
 will increase the importance of the price changes happening upstream compared to the competitive test result. In other words, price changes at the farm level 
 will be greater than those happening at the retail level 
 for a given move/change in the retail demand function. The 
 hint/result/effect is that price spreads should widen following such a demand shock. Given that the meat part/area 
 was likely to be subject to both sources of (coming from the outside of something) 
 change over the 1990s, the hit/effect on prices at each 
 up-and-down stage (and, by extension, the development of 
 
 350 
 
 T Lloyd et al. I Farming-based Money flow 25 (2001) 347-357 
 
 price spreads) will be the net result of both sources 
 of (coming from the outside of something) shocks to the beef part/area. More than that, 
 even if marketing costs and the demand curve shifted 
 by equal amounts, the move/change in the retail demand function should rule the hit/effect of the rise in the costs 
 connected with tighter legal/law-based standards. So, 
 unless the extent of marketing cost increases was 
 significantly greater than the direct effect of the food 
 scares (which is unlikely to be the case), good  we 
 should expect to watch/notice a widening of price spreads 
 over this period in the presence of market power. 
 
 2.2. Scientific issues 
 More and more studies focus on the scientific parts of price (change to make better/related to changing something) in the farming-based and 
 related markets. Because of the seen/obvious co-movement 
 in prices, many of these recent studies apply a 
 co-integration way(s) of doing things since it, (a) accounts appropriately for the time-series properties of the data 
 and, (b) measures the short-run and long-run nature 
 of price (change to make better/related to changing something). Examples of such studies include 
 von Cramon-Taubadel (1998), Chang and Griffith 
 (1998) and Goodwin and Holt (1999) among others. 
 The last thing just mentioned two papers differ from the earlier books 
 in that they focus on many stages of the marketing 
 chain by separately identifying price (change to make better/related to changing something) at 
 the farm, wholesale and retail levels, a practice that is 
 also followed in this paper. However, in most cases, 
 these scientific studies confine the sources of price 
 (change to make better/related to changing something) to be 'within' the food chain. (coming from the outside of something) influences, apart from a time (popular thing/general way things are going) or a given 
 (related to what holds something together and makes it strong) break, are not here. 
 In summary, (asking lots of questions about/trying to find the truth about) the hit/effect of food scares, 
 it is important to recognise that this type of (coming from the outside of something) 
 shock represents mostly a demand-side move/change to the 
 food part/area. As a result, it is reasonable to expect price 
 (change to make better/related to changing something) in the upstream stages of the marketing 
 chain. However, the extent of these price changes will 
 change/differ  between the stages if the downstream parts/areas 
 are seen as (not totally pure/not totally correct) competition. Although 
 the analysis of price (change to make better/related to changing something) is not a formal test 
 of market power, higher levels of price (change to make better/related to changing something) in 
 the upstream stages are certainly agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with it. 
 If the extent of price changes between each marketing stage differs/changes, this hints that the price spreads 
 (or marketing margin) will also change. Where 
 prices are non-unmoving and possibly show 
 
 co-movement, a co-integration (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built) offers an 
 appropriate way(s) of doing things for (thinking about/when one thinks about) the extent of 
 price (change to make better/related to changing something). The data and the role of food scares 
 on the beef market are organized and listed in the next section. 
 
 3. Data issues and 'food scares' 
 We employ real beef prices at the producer, wholesaler and store level (P1 , W1 and R 1 , (match up each pair of items in order)) 
 in England and Wales. The data have been calculated 
 by the Meat and Animals Commission and represent 
 dead body weight equals (CWE) to help direct 
 comparison of prices at all the three stages. The data 
 are monthly and cover the period from January 1990 
 to December 1998 (see Figs. 1 and 2). 2 They are (lowered/flattened from losing air) by the Retail Price Index (January 1999 base) 
 and clearly show a (lowering in number/getting worse) (popular thing/general way things are going) over the period. 
 Retail prices fell by 60 pence/kg, wholesale prices by 
 69 pence/kg and producer prices by 75 pence/kg over 
 the period. Casual (careful examination of something) of Fig. 1 also shows/tells about that 
 prices have a habit/desire to co-move, in that price movements at one level of the chain seem to be reflected in 
 prices in other places in the chain. 
 These price series are helped by a 'food 
 (being talked about a lot on TV, online, etc.) index', which is a count of the number of articles printed in broad-sheet newspapers on a monthly 
 basis that relate to the safety of meat. In general, 
 these reports are negative in nature and show the 
 concerns (related to/looking at/thinking about) the safety of meat, in terms of its 
 production and processing. Articles relating to BSE 
 rule the index although other almost the same  topics such 
 as health standards in slaughterhouses are also covered. The 
 index reflects personal concerns (related to/looking at/thinking about) the safety 
 parts of meat consumption and also the hit/effect of 
 regulation on the suppliers of meat. As a result, the 
 index will be related to the developments that 
 affect both the demand and supply of beef, though it 
 is likely to be the food scares issue that rules 
 given the public angere over BSE. In the scientific 
 analysis, the natural log of this index (represented it) is 
 used. A plot of the series is shown in Fig. 3. Increased Dickey-Fuller tests point to/show that each price 
 series and i1 are (having different things working together as one unit) of order 1 [/(1)]_), as visual 
 (careful examination of something) of Figs. 1 and 3 suggests. 
