 Co-integration is tested using methods developed by Johansen (1988). Following Stock and 
 Watson (1988), it is well known that with n (numbers that change/things that change) 
 there can be at the most n - l co-integrating relations 
 and n - r common (popular things/general ways things are going) in the system. Therefore, 
 with a triplet of prices, there can be at the most two 
 such co-integrating combinations, since if any two 
 pairs of prices co-move (co-integrate) then so must the 
 third. In this case, the prices share a single common 
 (popular thing/general way things are going) and may be expected to co-move over time. 
 Given the (problems, delays, etc.) that can be met understanding/explaining the coefficients of multiple co-integrating vectors (Ltitkepohl and Reimers, 1992) sudden desire response 
