 5. Results 
 As an first step, Eq. (1) is guessed for the price 
 triplet (Rt. W1 and P 1 ). An (having no limits, rules, or barriers) VAR(l2) 
 model, increased by four sudden desire dummy (numbers that change/things that change) 3 
 gives a good guess, such that extras/payments obey the stated ideas (you think are true) of e 1 in (1). 
 Given that prices are /(1), the model is examined 
 for the presence of co-integration suggested by the 
 co-movement of prices seen/obvious in Fig. l. Panel (a) 
 of Table 1 reports the co-integration test statistics for 
 this model. 
 While there appears to be an indication of 
 co-integration among the triplet, the formal (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) 
 is at the best weak. Specifically, the trace test statistic 
 rejects the null guess of no co-integration at the 
 5% importance, but the maximal eigenvalue test does 
 not. Also, the test statistics do not provide any 
 (enough to be meaningful) (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) of the multiple co-integrating relationships suggested by the pair-wise co-movement 
 of the data. One literal (understanding/ explanation) of this result is 
 that the beef markets are poorly (combined different things together so they worked as one unit). Or, the explanation might lie in the role of left-out 
 (numbers that change/things that change), especially, given the previous/coming before discus3 Dummies are for 1993(3), 1995(9), 1996(3) and 1996(4). While 
 they have a very small hit/effect on limit/guideline guesses, they are 
 included to make happy the (usual/ commonly and regular/ healthy)ity idea (you think is true). 
 
