 sion, the hit/effect of BSE and related health concerns 
 on price movements. 
 Increasing the price transmission model with (the 
 natural logarithm of) the food (being talked about a lot on TV, online, etc.) index it has a 
 marked effect on guessing. As the results in Panel (b) 
 of Table 1 show, (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) in favour of co-integration is 
 now much stronger: the trace and maximal eigenvalue 
 test statistics now reject the null of no co-integration at 
 the 1% importance level. More than that, both tests suggest 
 the presence of three co-integrating vectors, a result 
 agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with pair-wise co-movement (in combination with the food scares (number or thing that changes)). 4 The clear end of/final opinion of the co-integration analysis is that the food 
 (being talked about a lot on TV, online, etc.) index plays an important in the long-run (change over time) of the UK beef prices and that once the effect 
 of the index is taken into account, prices co-move in 
 a manner agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with market (combination of different things together that work as one unit). 
 The above result begs some questions, not 
 least those relating to the exact role that the food 
 (being talked about a lot on TV, online, etc.) index plays in price (creation and construction/ group of objects). To (ask lots of questions about/try to find the truth about) 
 this issue, Fig. 4 shows the orthogonalised sudden desire 
 response functions of the three beef prices to a unit 
 ( 1%) shock in the food (being talked about a lot on TV, online, etc.) index. These point to/show 
 that the increased (being talked about a lot on TV, online, etc.) (related to/looking at/thinking about) food safety at first increases beef prices at all stages of the marketing chain, but that after that, they fall. The long-run 
 effect is negative on all beef prices, with the guesses 
 suggesting that retail, wholesale and producer prices 
 fall by 1.70, 2.25 and 3.0 pence/kg, (match up each pair of items in order). This 
 goes along with a food (being talked about a lot on TV, online, etc.) ability to stretch of around 
 1.4. 5 
 As an helping to these results, forecast error rottings may also be calculated. These guess the 
 proportion of the total variance of each of the prices 
 that is due to an orthogonalised shock measured at clearly stated/particular periods of time (or space) following this shock (Hamilton, 1994 ). 
 The results suggest that the effects on prices stabilise 
 some 30 months following a shock to the index which 
 accounts for about 6, 11 and 61% of the difference/different version in the retail, wholesale and producer prices, (match up each pair of items in order). 
 4 Using the limited sample correction to the asymptotic critical 
 values suggested by Reimers (1992) does not change this end/end result, although the P-values of the test are conespondingly larger. 
 Specifically, while the null of no cointegration cannot be rejected 
