 The results show two features: (1) That the 
 UK beef prices were (able to reply or react/quick to respond) to the public's knowledge of food safety issues (mostly BSE) in the 
 1990s but (2) that the hit/effect was not common across 
 stages in the marketing chain. This second point hints that price spreads also move in a planned way in response to (being talked about a lot on TV, online, etc.) about the safety of food. Shocks to 
 the food (being talked about a lot on TV, online, etc.) index cause the wholesale-producer 
 price spreads to expand more than the retail-wholesale 
 price spreads. More than that, the difference between retail and producer prices, the measure that receives 
 most attention in the public debate on this issue, rises 
 by an even larger amount in response to BSE (being talked about a lot on TV, online, etc.). Specifically, a 1% increase in the food (being talked about a lot on TV, online, etc.) index causes a 0.5 pence/kg increase in the 
 retail-wholesale spread, 0.75 pence/kg increase in the 
 wholesale-producer spread and so a 1.25 pence/kg 
 increase in the retail-producer spread. Given that the 
 media interest has generally risen over the sample period, price spreads are watched/followed to rise over time. 
 The (instance of watching, noticing, or making a statement) that the food (being talked about a lot on TV, online, etc.) index should 
 lead to (lower in number/get worse) in prices at each marketing stage is, to 
 a large degree, expected and agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with the control of the demand relative to supply sources (i.e. 
 due to increased regulation) of (coming from the outside of something) shocks in 
 the beef part/area over the 1990s. That this price decline 
 should change/differ  between stages is a little more surprising, 
 especially given the nature of the data which, being 
 agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with fixed proportions technology, might 
 otherwise suggest that all the price declines be equal. 
 The fact that these price declines change/differ  between stages, 
 leading to a widening of price spreads, is a strong sign of 
 a food chain seen as some degree of market 
 power at wholesale and retail stages. 
 
 6. Ends/end results 
 This paper has focussed on the hit/effect of (being talked about a lot on TV, online, etc.), mostly concerns relating to BSE, on 
 price transmission in the UK beef part/area during the 
 1990s. Admitting/recognizing/responding to the co-movement that exists 
 between prices in the meat marketing chain, we use a 
 co-integrating (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built), the results of which show 
 the importance of information, as included in a 
 food (being talked about a lot on TV, online, etc.) index, in price transmission. Prices at 
 all levels have tended to decrease during the 1990s, 
 a result that is agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with inward moves/changes of the 
 
 T. Lloyd et a!./Agricultural Money flow 25 (2001) 347-357 
 
 demand function. Maybe more interesting is that the 
 extent of price (change to make better/related to changing something) differs/changes between marketing 
 stages. Especially, prices at the retail (wholesale) 
 level decline but less so than prices at the wholesale 
 (farm) level. While supply side shocks may also have 
 been seen/obvious in the UK beef part/area over the 1990s 
 due to increased regulation, the fact that widening 
 margins are watched/followed suggests the control of 
 demand-side moves/changes in a market that does not go along with/match up to a perfectly competitive model. Although 
 the results presented in this paper do not make up/be equal to a 
 formal test of market power, they lend support to the 
 UK's Competition Commission (act of asking questions and trying to find the truth about something) into the 
 degree of market power in the food part/area. A more 
 formal test for market power in (up and down) integrated 
 markets is the subject of our on-going research. 
 
